1
00:00:04,458 --> 00:00:07,821
The following interview is of City Council candidate David Tedisco.

2
00:00:08,922 --> 00:00:15,728
Information for this introduction was taken from David's campaign website, which is linked in the show notes for further reading.

3
00:00:16,649 --> 00:00:23,955
David has been working and volunteering in politics since his days as class president at Medford High School, a position he held for three years.

4
00:00:25,036 --> 00:00:28,999
At the age of 18, David interned for State Representative Sean Garibelli.

5
00:00:29,620 --> 00:00:38,827
He also worked on Hillary Clinton's 2016 presidential campaign in New Hampshire, learning the importance of engaging with the community to understand the issues people faced.

6
00:00:39,788 --> 00:00:46,493
At the age of 19, David was asked to be the campaign coordinator for former Medford Mayor Stephanie Eugenie Burke.

7
00:00:48,163 --> 00:00:54,967
His time working with this campaign gave him a deeper insight into Medford politics and the challenges that Medford residents face today.

8
00:00:55,887 --> 00:00:57,668
Recently, David was working in D.C.

9
00:00:57,769 --> 00:01:03,652
in the office of Congresswoman Lori Trahan as his Press Secretary and Digital Director.

10
00:01:04,752 --> 00:01:17,680
In his campaign for City Council, David is focused on implementing a citywide infrastructure plan, modernizing city services, and revitalizing Medford Square into a thriving downtown area replete with diverse local businesses.

11
00:01:19,583 --> 00:01:23,210
Interviews for this podcast are done in a way to ensure COVID safety.

12
00:01:23,731 --> 00:01:27,878
For that reason, you may notice the sound of rain in the background of this episode.

13
00:01:28,579 --> 00:01:29,281
Thanks for listening.

14
00:01:34,949 --> 00:01:35,410
Hi, David.

15
00:01:35,430 --> 00:01:36,932
Thanks so much for joining me today.

16
00:01:37,332 --> 00:01:38,714
Danielle, thank you for having me.

17
00:01:38,874 --> 00:01:39,675
This is amazing.

18
00:01:40,015 --> 00:01:40,776
Oh, no, no worries.

19
00:01:40,856 --> 00:01:41,757
I'm glad you could be here.

20
00:01:42,598 --> 00:01:48,384
So to start off, I've been asking folks that I interview about their favorite choice for a place to get a bite to eat in Medford.

21
00:01:48,404 --> 00:01:49,866
So what is yours?

22
00:01:50,146 --> 00:01:54,651
Well, I don't think it's much of a secret about me, but I'm Tenoch's biggest fan.

23
00:01:56,113 --> 00:01:57,634
Been going there since they opened.

24
00:01:58,235 --> 00:02:03,319
I was in high school, it was either 2014, and I remember I was at Papagino's in the square.

25
00:02:03,339 --> 00:02:07,642
I had just eaten a full pizza and I looked across the street and saw a burrito place.

26
00:02:08,423 --> 00:02:13,146
Keep in mind I weighed like 260 pounds at the time, but I looked across the street and I was like, a burrito?

27
00:02:13,647 --> 00:02:19,612
And I did have a full burrito after having this pizza and fell in love that day and have been going to Tenoch.

28
00:02:20,312 --> 00:02:24,274
ever since, but I try not to have both a full pizza and burrito consistently now.

29
00:02:24,474 --> 00:02:25,455
Try to do one or the other.

30
00:02:25,535 --> 00:02:27,836
That's a good adult life choice.

31
00:02:27,856 --> 00:02:39,043
Yeah, trying to be healthier as an adult, not a high schooler, but yeah, just very Tenoch proud and always trying to send people there and order their food whenever I can.

32
00:02:39,603 --> 00:02:41,044
So is a burrito your go-to there?

33
00:02:42,064 --> 00:02:48,207
I actually, and I'm not going to pronounce this correctly, but plato mexicano, which is just like a burrito on a plate, pretty much.

34
00:02:48,827 --> 00:02:51,388
And it's rice, beans, and you can do chicken or steak.

35
00:02:51,469 --> 00:02:57,871
And their secret, a lot of people don't know about, is mole, which is their chocolate sauce that's spicy.

36
00:02:58,332 --> 00:03:00,673
It's not sweet, but it's really, really amazing.

37
00:03:00,753 --> 00:03:05,135
And I think Tenoch is such a great example of,

38
00:03:06,650 --> 00:03:27,443
one of the really cool hidden gems in Medford and Medford Square, and just represents, right, the diversity we currently have in the local business scene and how do we continue to expand upon that and bring different cultures in, because we're all, you know, if you look down Medford Square on a Friday night, I think it's Nigea, the sushi, all-you-can-eat sushi place.

39
00:03:27,844 --> 00:03:29,205
There's like always a line out the door.

40
00:03:29,425 --> 00:03:30,105
It's unreal.

41
00:03:31,266 --> 00:03:33,848
So people really love these diverse options and, of course,

42
00:03:34,908 --> 00:03:35,469
day one.

43
00:03:35,749 --> 00:03:41,472
I grew up eating Bob's Subs in South Medford so I always have to do a shout out to Bob's as well.

44
00:03:42,372 --> 00:03:45,134
I love hearing other people's experiences of these places.

45
00:03:45,234 --> 00:03:50,237
Yeah I know and I'm trying to think like you know of course Medford Brewing is opening up on Harvard Ave.

46
00:03:50,397 --> 00:03:51,277
Yeah it is Harvard Ave.

47
00:03:52,598 --> 00:04:05,683
hopefully in the next six months like we're you know just adding to the scene and it's it's exciting stuff and exciting like the direction we're going in of just having more and more uh different options on the menu you know so

48
00:04:06,780 --> 00:04:07,140
Cool.

49
00:04:07,501 --> 00:04:11,004
You talked about your involvement in Medford.

50
00:04:11,044 --> 00:04:12,885
And we talked a little bit about it in the intro.

51
00:04:12,925 --> 00:04:17,790
And you've got a lot of experience interacting with local businesses.

52
00:04:17,810 --> 00:04:26,137
But I'm just interested in hearing about what led you to run for city council and your path to local politics.

53
00:04:26,377 --> 00:04:28,900
Yeah, my path to local politics.

54
00:04:29,060 --> 00:04:35,246
So I was a junior in high school and my brother Dennis was really successful.

55
00:04:35,306 --> 00:04:43,795
He started a clothing company at the time and like a larger brand called Karma Loop bought his brand and he was doing really great.

56
00:04:44,235 --> 00:04:47,678
And so I said to myself, I want to go into business because I want to make money because that's

57
00:04:48,319 --> 00:04:48,919
That's cool.

58
00:04:49,660 --> 00:04:55,944
And then junior year history, I had a teacher named Jonathan Streff, who's still at the high school now.

59
00:04:56,725 --> 00:05:00,948
And I somehow, by the skin of my teeth, got into APUS.

60
00:05:01,768 --> 00:05:03,109
I think it was APUS history.

61
00:05:04,190 --> 00:05:13,114
And he just opened my eyes to the importance of civic engagement and being a part of something so much greater than yourself.

62
00:05:14,415 --> 00:05:21,618
And so it's when I kind of changed my focus to maybe I don't want to go to business school, maybe I want to get involved in public life.

63
00:05:23,925 --> 00:05:30,652
Even though, and it's so true, and I learned this lesson later on, jobs don't pay well in the public sector.

64
00:05:30,712 --> 00:05:38,099
So, you know, it's really an issue of equity and making the sector more attractive so we have people invest more in our society.

65
00:05:40,265 --> 00:05:52,974
But yeah, I mean, Jonathan Streff, he was the type of guy that, I mean, on the weekends, he was a national park ranger at JFK's birth home in Brookline and would do civil war reenactments on the weekend.

66
00:05:53,155 --> 00:05:57,978
Like this is a guy that currently lives and breathes the history, you know?

67
00:05:58,018 --> 00:06:00,300
So he really just spread that passion.

68
00:06:00,340 --> 00:06:04,103
And the funny thing is, if you look at my campaign today, right, my campaign,

69
00:06:06,393 --> 00:06:22,923
Our core team, it's a ton of people from my high school class and specifically a lot of students that had strep in particular and I think they kind of caught the bug the same way I did of this is so cool and exciting and you're part of something so much greater than just you.

70
00:06:23,643 --> 00:06:26,965
So that was when I kind of mentally got first invested in politics.

71
00:06:29,518 --> 00:06:37,561
Then I went, you know, after Medford High, I went to UMass Lowell, and I remember I was at the club fair, and there was like a huge Donald Trump table.

72
00:06:38,581 --> 00:06:43,463
And this was at UMass Lowell, which I perceived to be like a more, you know, democratic university.

73
00:06:44,243 --> 00:06:50,005
And of course, there's strength and diversity of opinions, but I was just disheartened that I didn't see like a college Democrats table.

74
00:06:50,586 --> 00:06:54,347
So I went over to the Trump table, and I said, where's the college Democrats?

75
00:06:54,407 --> 00:06:56,708
And they, you know, they just smiled and said, they don't exist.

76
00:06:57,728 --> 00:06:58,849
And I couldn't believe it.

77
00:06:58,909 --> 00:07:01,690
So I started College Democrats at UMass Lowell.

78
00:07:02,291 --> 00:07:04,972
I mean, it's still going today, a really strong organization.

79
00:07:05,052 --> 00:07:10,716
But it was exciting because at the time, a congressional primary was going on.

80
00:07:11,436 --> 00:07:16,039
Nikki Songhus, who represented the Merrimack Valley, was stepping down.

81
00:07:17,039 --> 00:07:21,442
And so I met basically all the candidates because they wanted to come in and talk to our club.

82
00:07:21,462 --> 00:07:23,383
They wanted to get young people involved.

83
00:07:24,283 --> 00:07:27,987
in civic life and really get college Democrats on board their campaigns.

84
00:07:28,027 --> 00:07:31,691
So I met Rufus Gifford, Dan Coe, Lori Trahan.

85
00:07:33,702 --> 00:07:36,104
I ended up joining Rufus Gifford's campaign.

86
00:07:36,584 --> 00:07:41,468
And Rufus was the fundraiser for President Obama.

87
00:07:41,668 --> 00:07:43,990
He was later appointed ambassador to Denmark.

88
00:07:44,490 --> 00:07:53,437
He was so deep in public life and really saw the importance of being involved and playing your role in whatever capacity that may be.

89
00:07:54,768 --> 00:07:56,429
Rufus came in fifth place.

90
00:07:57,649 --> 00:08:01,090
That race didn't work out, but Rufus inspired me so much.

91
00:08:02,150 --> 00:08:02,951
So many things about Rufus.

92
00:08:02,971 --> 00:08:05,811
You know, he was an openly gay candidate running for Congress.

93
00:08:06,352 --> 00:08:09,593
I was very much and always am in the process of coming out, right?

94
00:08:09,613 --> 00:08:11,773
Because everyone you meet, you're always coming out to.

95
00:08:11,813 --> 00:08:15,274
It's like introducing any other element of your personality.

96
00:08:15,834 --> 00:08:17,055
But he just really inspired me.

97
00:08:17,075 --> 00:08:23,097
He was so proud and secure of who he was and had such a vision and passion for what America should be.

98
00:08:25,399 --> 00:08:26,439
And so I joined Rufus.

99
00:08:26,479 --> 00:08:27,199
It didn't work out.

100
00:08:27,840 --> 00:08:33,121
I ended up getting a scholarship to American University and going to grad school in Washington, DC.

101
00:08:33,941 --> 00:08:35,581
And I'm sitting there.

102
00:08:35,641 --> 00:08:37,002
I got a job in admissions.

103
00:08:37,662 --> 00:08:44,964
And I'm thinking, I know so much about this congressional district in Massachusetts, 37 cities and towns.

104
00:08:45,364 --> 00:08:47,264
And this knowledge is just being wasted.

105
00:08:47,844 --> 00:08:50,245
And so I called up Lori Trahan, who had won.

106
00:08:50,265 --> 00:08:51,605
And I knew of her.

107
00:08:51,645 --> 00:08:52,145
And she knew of me.

108
00:08:52,165 --> 00:08:53,966
And I was still very supportive of her.

109
00:08:55,766 --> 00:08:59,888
And after enough pestering, she said, all right, I'll take you on board.

110
00:08:59,928 --> 00:09:02,709
So I ended up joining her office, I think, February.

111
00:09:02,949 --> 00:09:04,269
She got it sworn in in January.

112
00:09:04,329 --> 00:09:05,750
I joined her team in February.

113
00:09:06,510 --> 00:09:10,911
Started off as her digital assistant, and then became her digital director and press secretary.

114
00:09:12,872 --> 00:09:22,101
And so that kind of takes me up to the point when I started to think about running for city council because what happened in my life happened in everyone else's life.

115
00:09:22,121 --> 00:09:25,484
The COVID-19 pandemic hit and kind of rocked everyone's world.

116
00:09:27,918 --> 00:09:40,722
And so I started watching city council meetings over Zoom because at the federal level, we were working on these large spending bills, the CARES package, the American Rescue Plan, the Families First Act, right?

117
00:09:40,742 --> 00:09:44,223
All these big, big spending bills filled with COVID-19 relief.

118
00:09:44,243 --> 00:09:45,503
And there was a lot in them.

119
00:09:45,523 --> 00:09:46,804
There was small business relief.

120
00:09:47,184 --> 00:09:50,165
There was testing resources, vaccine funding.

121
00:09:51,965 --> 00:09:54,869
simple things like PPE, right, the personal protective equipment.

122
00:09:55,590 --> 00:10:02,619
And so I was watching city council to see how are we talking about these big spending bills at the local level.

123
00:10:02,700 --> 00:10:04,882
You know, I know how we're talking about them at the U.S.

124
00:10:04,902 --> 00:10:06,204
Capitol, what's going on at home.

125
00:10:08,877 --> 00:10:16,400
I tuned in, and I think I experienced what a lot of residents experience, which was really shocked by the state of the council.

126
00:10:17,560 --> 00:10:18,501
It was really divided.

127
00:10:18,521 --> 00:10:23,163
The discourse got really low at times, and I know it was a tough two years.

128
00:10:23,243 --> 00:10:26,484
But I've elected you to represent me and 58,000 other people.

129
00:10:29,265 --> 00:10:35,289
And I just always hope we keep the bar high and always maintain respect even when we disagree.

130
00:10:35,489 --> 00:10:41,053
We can disagree on opinion, but acknowledge we're still neighbors, right?

131
00:10:41,193 --> 00:10:44,015
And the important thing is that we need to educate each other.

132
00:10:44,175 --> 00:10:51,559
We need to educate each other about our stances so that you understand why I believe black lives matter and why I believe love is love, right?

133
00:10:51,599 --> 00:10:52,560
These are important things.

134
00:10:52,620 --> 00:10:54,421
It's not just a lawn sign.

135
00:10:54,441 --> 00:10:56,623
These affect people's lives and well-being.

136
00:10:59,029 --> 00:11:08,838
And so I just, you know, it was also the peak of the Black Lives Matter movement, and I was working in lockstep with Mobilize Medford, and we organized a letter which went out.

137
00:11:09,479 --> 00:11:18,087
Over 700 residents signed on to this letter, which basically said, hey, city administrators, thanks so much for declaring racism a public health crisis.

138
00:11:18,388 --> 00:11:19,609
It really was an important thing, right?

139
00:11:19,629 --> 00:11:20,209
It unlocked

140
00:11:21,370 --> 00:11:25,374
special funding from the state that we wouldn't receive had we not declared that.

141
00:11:25,894 --> 00:11:28,216
But many also saw it as a Band-Aid solution.

142
00:11:28,476 --> 00:11:31,819
What did that really do beyond that wonderful claim?

143
00:11:32,299 --> 00:11:34,221
What are we doing to make systemic change?

144
00:11:35,662 --> 00:11:43,628
And so this letter we wrote outlined six different priorities of here are things you can do in the city of Medford to actually make Medford more equitable.

145
00:11:43,648 --> 00:11:48,032
And I think that's where it gets into many other policy areas, which I'm happy to dive into.

146
00:11:50,242 --> 00:11:53,725
And so the response to that was really nothing.

147
00:11:54,506 --> 00:11:57,509
Some folks emailed back, but there was no follow-up.

148
00:11:57,589 --> 00:11:59,651
There was no actionable change.

149
00:12:00,312 --> 00:12:03,094
And so I took a step back, and you look at the bigger picture.

150
00:12:03,114 --> 00:12:05,156
And you say, all right, we're not really delivering.

151
00:12:06,317 --> 00:12:08,098
for every population in Medford.

152
00:12:08,138 --> 00:12:10,500
We're not really delivering on the basic services.

153
00:12:10,540 --> 00:12:12,341
I mean, I looked at, right, I live in North Medford.

154
00:12:12,641 --> 00:12:14,862
You look at the state of the streets and the sidewalks.

155
00:12:15,483 --> 00:12:18,204
And that's what I got my master's in was public administration.

156
00:12:18,224 --> 00:12:25,268
And my degree was really focused on municipal planning and infrastructure and finance and the intersectionality of all these issues.

157
00:12:27,768 --> 00:12:34,612
And so I just, I said to myself, we're really not delivering so many of the basic things that our neighbors are.

158
00:12:35,432 --> 00:12:40,115
Malden is, Somerville is, Cambridge is, Melrose is, on a lot of these issues.

159
00:12:40,815 --> 00:12:43,636
And so I said to myself, all right, we need new blood in Medford.

160
00:12:44,717 --> 00:12:48,139
I'll be honest, I've always been more of a behind the scenes guy, right?

161
00:12:48,179 --> 00:12:51,820
I worked for Mayor Burke, managed her campaign in 2017.

162
00:12:53,161 --> 00:12:59,183
I worked on the Biden campaign from home, making calls all day, worked on Secretary Clinton's campaign.

163
00:12:59,224 --> 00:13:02,285
Like, you know, I've always been behind the scenes working on these elements.

164
00:13:02,665 --> 00:13:09,788
Never pictured myself as a candidate until I was talking to a lot of my friends and family this spring about, you know, who are we gonna run?

165
00:13:10,368 --> 00:13:13,450
Asking around, I'll happily manage a campaign.

166
00:13:14,211 --> 00:13:16,354
And a few folks were like, well, why don't you just run?

167
00:13:16,915 --> 00:13:17,475
Why don't you run?

168
00:13:17,496 --> 00:13:21,682
And I said, well, you know, I don't know if that's right for me right now.

169
00:13:21,782 --> 00:13:27,690
I had already moved home because the pandemic got so bad that I decided to move home.

170
00:13:29,392 --> 00:13:36,197
mid-2020 because I was paying rent in DC, but because I could be home, I was home.

171
00:13:36,537 --> 00:13:39,519
I said, why am I paying rent in DC when I really want to be back in Medford?

172
00:13:39,939 --> 00:13:44,142
The idea was to move there, get the degree, and come back home, and that just really happened to work out.

173
00:13:46,690 --> 00:13:56,252
That's, you know, the pandemic had very few silver linings, but I view them as, that is one of them of, it really prompted this internal look on yourself.

174
00:13:56,332 --> 00:13:57,193
What do you prioritize?

175
00:13:57,213 --> 00:13:57,993
What do you want in life?

176
00:13:58,433 --> 00:14:02,634
And I realized, like, I'm not spending enough time with my family, especially in a public health crisis.

177
00:14:02,654 --> 00:14:05,955
You realize not everyone's here for as long as you'd like them to be.

178
00:14:05,975 --> 00:14:08,235
So you've got to spend time with those that mean the world to you.

179
00:14:10,756 --> 00:14:12,557
So I know I went a little bit all over the map here.

180
00:14:12,597 --> 00:14:12,837
Sorry.

181
00:14:12,877 --> 00:14:18,760
EMILY FORTUNA No, you touched on a lot of the different things that I was going to ask you.

182
00:14:18,780 --> 00:14:23,702
Sort of like what your observations have been, what you'd like to change, or what you'd like to see done differently.

183
00:14:24,262 --> 00:14:25,923
And I also would agree.

184
00:14:28,764 --> 00:14:32,327
Lots of people have become more engaged in local politics and watching the city council.

185
00:14:32,647 --> 00:14:37,871
The access with Zoom, for me at least, made things really easy to participate.

186
00:14:37,991 --> 00:14:39,352
And we need to keep that, right?

187
00:14:39,412 --> 00:14:43,275
That is dropping the barriers to civic engagement.

188
00:14:43,415 --> 00:14:46,518
How are we allowing a city like Medford, right?

189
00:14:46,558 --> 00:14:47,499
We're not Boston.

190
00:14:47,719 --> 00:14:51,802
We don't have the press that Boston has or even Cambridge or Somerville.

191
00:14:52,062 --> 00:14:59,447
We're lucky to have the transcript, and Kinga, who's a new reporter here in Medford, we're lucky to have her in the organization.

192
00:14:59,467 --> 00:15:01,348
But we always need more coverage.

193
00:15:01,929 --> 00:15:06,131
And the most important thing we can do is expose people directly to government.

194
00:15:06,772 --> 00:15:09,053
See what the people you've elected are like.

195
00:15:09,353 --> 00:15:10,114
How do they talk?

196
00:15:10,174 --> 00:15:11,134
What do they care about?

197
00:15:11,475 --> 00:15:13,216
Are they reflecting your priorities?

198
00:15:15,117 --> 00:15:22,446
And I think over the last two years, a lot of us had that internal look, you know, looking in the mirror as a city.

199
00:15:23,087 --> 00:15:26,211
What do we want to prioritize over the next two years?

200
00:15:28,337 --> 00:15:35,424
And so yeah, that is why Zoom is so important and in any barrier for anyone to get engaged in the conversation is critical.

201
00:15:35,824 --> 00:15:45,453
And there's so many ways that we can open up the conversation to make city government more accessible to all different populations that historically have been shut out of the conversation.

202
00:15:46,414 --> 00:15:49,877
But I just want to touch upon why this moment matters.

203
00:15:51,178 --> 00:15:56,182
We have $48 million coming to the city of Medford from the American Rescue Plan.

204
00:15:56,743 --> 00:15:58,644
And I know some folks are starting to talk about this.

205
00:15:59,485 --> 00:16:08,933
I've been mentioning this since May on the campaign trail because I worked on the messaging of the legislation back when I was working for the Congresswoman.

206
00:16:08,973 --> 00:16:14,298
So I was very mindful of this huge influx of federal funds coming to Medford.

207
00:16:15,739 --> 00:16:18,920
We're adding about a whole fourth to our regular municipal budget.

208
00:16:19,040 --> 00:16:24,683
I mean, it's really a remarkable opportunity to get through some serious backlog on projects, right?

209
00:16:25,144 --> 00:16:28,525
Of course, first and foremost, we should be prioritizing the public health crisis.

210
00:16:28,846 --> 00:16:30,767
That's what these dollars were dedicated for.

211
00:16:31,307 --> 00:16:32,428
So, Medford High School.

212
00:16:33,441 --> 00:16:35,424
I graduated Medford High in 2015.

213
00:16:36,005 --> 00:16:37,026
I was class president.

214
00:16:37,547 --> 00:16:43,235
Couldn't have been more proud of the people in that building and the educators and the administrators and the student body.

215
00:16:43,736 --> 00:16:46,480
The physical building is lacking dramatically.

216
00:16:47,040 --> 00:16:48,883
I'm not the only one to notice this, of course.

217
00:16:49,810 --> 00:16:53,073
but we still don't have proper ventilation at the high school.

218
00:16:53,693 --> 00:17:02,341
You know, we can claim we do because we've unlocked some metal windows that were locked up in the 80s or 90s, but that doesn't mean we have proper ventilation.

219
00:17:02,881 --> 00:17:04,442
You know, the other element is,

220
00:17:06,499 --> 00:17:09,140
There is that conversation about do we get a new high school.

221
00:17:09,580 --> 00:17:14,763
You know, we've invested so much in B building and the new pool and the new field of dreams.

222
00:17:15,703 --> 00:17:18,044
But the important thing is we've got to start that conversation.

223
00:17:18,084 --> 00:17:20,585
This project is going to take seven years no matter what.

224
00:17:21,346 --> 00:17:23,987
And how can these federal funds assist with that?

225
00:17:24,127 --> 00:17:27,629
So I think first and foremost, right, if a new high school is going to take seven years,

226
00:17:28,409 --> 00:17:32,071
we should be updating the ventilation immediately, immediately with these federal funds.

227
00:17:32,091 --> 00:17:33,551
That's what they were dedicated for.

228
00:17:33,831 --> 00:17:35,412
And I'm talking about air controlled rooms.

229
00:17:35,492 --> 00:17:40,154
You know, it is against state law for a public facility to be above 80 degrees Fahrenheit.

230
00:17:40,574 --> 00:17:43,455
Yet it happens at Medford High every September, May, and June.

231
00:17:43,996 --> 00:17:45,736
And that's because it was grandfathered in.

232
00:17:45,917 --> 00:17:48,057
It was built before the state law was put in place.

233
00:17:48,438 --> 00:17:51,419
But the reality is, is the state law was put in place for a reason.

234
00:17:51,819 --> 00:17:53,600
It's unsafe for students with disability.

235
00:17:55,101 --> 00:18:04,387
And unsafe, you know, in general, if you can't focus because you're so uncomfortable in a hot room, how are you paying attention to your education?

236
00:18:05,008 --> 00:18:07,510
And this is where we fall behind compared to our neighbors.

237
00:18:08,150 --> 00:18:17,917
You know, if you think about it, a student sweating in a classroom in Medford, probably not going to get as good grades as a student who's very comfortable in Winchester, just able to easily pay attention to the curriculum.

238
00:18:18,297 --> 00:18:21,019
That is where the gap begins to grow when we don't invest.

239
00:18:23,247 --> 00:18:42,474
And so that's why these federal funds are a really exciting opportunity, getting proper ventilation at the high school, starting an infrastructure plan across the city of Medford to update our streets and our sidewalks, not only so that they're well paved, but that they're ADA compliant, and being mindful of climate resiliency every step of the way.

240
00:18:43,514 --> 00:18:45,535
I'm not going to claim I'm the climate expert.

241
00:18:46,700 --> 00:18:51,244
I think that's a problem right now with any leader in this country who's elected.

242
00:18:51,665 --> 00:18:52,946
You don't have to be the expert.

243
00:18:53,286 --> 00:18:56,189
You didn't get a PhD in environmental policy.

244
00:18:56,630 --> 00:18:58,852
But your job is to get those people in the room.

245
00:18:59,252 --> 00:19:01,294
Have them advise you on what is best.

246
00:19:01,735 --> 00:19:04,117
The public health crisis showed that best, right?

247
00:19:04,477 --> 00:19:05,719
You don't have to be the doctor.

248
00:19:07,340 --> 00:19:17,124
but get the doctor in the room to tell you the best thing, not Facebook, but a real medical professional to tell you, you know, should you be wearing a mask?

249
00:19:17,184 --> 00:19:18,225
Should you get vaccinated?

250
00:19:18,345 --> 00:19:19,545
Let them do the research.

251
00:19:19,585 --> 00:19:20,446
That's their job.

252
00:19:20,846 --> 00:19:21,706
And you do your job.

253
00:19:21,726 --> 00:19:23,047
Maybe your job's an educator.

254
00:19:23,087 --> 00:19:24,187
Maybe your job's a coach.

255
00:19:24,227 --> 00:19:28,369
Maybe your job is working at a grocery store or helping pave a road.

256
00:19:28,409 --> 00:19:35,472
I mean, we all play such a critical role in society and let the experts do what they've studied, you know?

257
00:19:37,373 --> 00:19:45,462
Yeah, no, and it sounds like you have a lot of things that you would like to change or like to continue seeing work done on in the city.

258
00:19:46,022 --> 00:19:47,544
Do you have any thoughts about equity?

259
00:19:47,784 --> 00:19:54,331
You've addressed this in a little bit of your response already, but what Medford would need to become more equitable?

260
00:19:54,651 --> 00:19:54,971
Yeah.

