00:19:55,111 --> 00:20:11,976
And I know a few other candidates have touched upon this in the pod series as well, which real quick, just before I jump into equity, I just want to say like, Danielle, the fact that you wrote about this podcast on Facebook a week and a half ago, and it is up and running now, and you have four episodes.

262
00:20:12,056 --> 00:20:12,897
It's just remarkable.

263
00:20:12,937 --> 00:20:15,978
And I think that's so symbolic of Medford residents.

264
00:20:16,018 --> 00:20:18,738
Like we have an idea and we want to put it to action.

265
00:20:18,798 --> 00:20:20,519
We just need a government that matches that.

266
00:20:21,840 --> 00:20:28,588
But I've just been so blown away by how you got this up and running, and a brand, and a logo, and it's on Spotify.

267
00:20:29,769 --> 00:20:31,011
I'm very, very impressed.

268
00:20:31,171 --> 00:20:33,714
So thank you for doing that and moving so fast.

269
00:20:35,096 --> 00:20:35,796
Back to equity.

270
00:20:36,738 --> 00:20:41,703
Also to say, I couldn't have done it without the accessibility of the candidates that have come on.

271
00:20:41,723 --> 00:20:44,487
They've made it sort of easy to schedule things.

272
00:20:44,587 --> 00:20:45,728
That is awesome, right.

273
00:20:46,089 --> 00:20:52,616
And that's where a responsive government comes into the conversation, especially folks who are running to be your elected officials.

274
00:20:55,658 --> 00:21:03,801
Charter review, and if you've listened to other episodes, I apologize for repeating what charter review is, but charter review is basically our local constitution.

275
00:21:04,081 --> 00:21:06,442
It is how do we decide what our government looks like?

276
00:21:07,022 --> 00:21:09,203
We haven't done this in Medford in 38 years.

277
00:21:09,963 --> 00:21:14,004
Most communities build in an internal review every five to 10 years.

278
00:21:14,064 --> 00:21:14,905
It's just a given.

279
00:21:15,725 --> 00:21:21,387
And I think that's intentional for many reasons that we haven't had that review.

280
00:21:23,080 --> 00:21:28,204
What we desperately need in Medford is ward representation and at-large representation.

281
00:21:28,764 --> 00:21:31,987
Right now, I believe, Medford, we have eight wards in Medford.

282
00:21:32,247 --> 00:21:34,329
Two of our eight wards are represented on the council.

283
00:21:35,090 --> 00:21:37,331
Eight of our eight wards should be represented on the council.

284
00:21:38,332 --> 00:21:40,853
And so it's a system Malden has.

285
00:21:40,993 --> 00:21:43,213
It's worked incredibly well for them.

286
00:21:44,173 --> 00:21:44,893
Somerville has it.

287
00:21:44,933 --> 00:21:46,494
Cambridge has it.

288
00:21:47,374 --> 00:21:55,396
It allows each neighborhood to be more engaged, to have someone more responsive to their issues, and actually have a city council that looks like the city of Medford.

289
00:21:55,936 --> 00:22:00,617
And so I think that that's a domino effect for equity across the city, right?

290
00:22:02,317 --> 00:22:08,559
I got asked this question, what can we do to welcome more minority businesses to the city of Medford, minority-owned businesses?

291
00:22:09,739 --> 00:22:10,600
There's a number of things.

292
00:22:10,780 --> 00:22:12,320
We could have the chamber reach out more.

293
00:22:12,360 --> 00:22:20,142
We could ensure our city communications are multilingual, consistently, not just here or there, but across the board.

294
00:22:22,284 --> 00:22:29,354
make government services and communications much more accessible through a 3-1-1 system and easily access City Hall 24-7.

295
00:22:30,115 --> 00:22:36,204
But really, I would imagine if you're opening up, let's say, a pizza shop in Medford,

296
00:22:37,385 --> 00:22:41,028
you're going to look at what do the local elected officials look like?

297
00:22:41,188 --> 00:22:42,229
What does the scene look like?

298
00:22:42,709 --> 00:22:45,992
And then you might decide from there, is this the community that's right for my business?

299
00:22:46,472 --> 00:22:53,157
If we have a city council that actually looks like the population of Medford, I'm sure minority-owned businesses would feel more comfortable opening up shop here.

300
00:22:53,798 --> 00:22:57,921
We only have one black-owned business in Medford, Neighborhood Kitchen, which is great.

301
00:22:58,701 --> 00:23:01,003
But how do we open that up?

302
00:23:01,203 --> 00:23:06,007
You know, in talking about, we have so much opportunity coming, Mystic Avenue, right?

303
00:23:07,317 --> 00:23:14,359
I know that we've had a lot of folks kind of stop the progress that should have happened already on Mystic Avenue when you start talking about our housing shortage.

304
00:23:14,959 --> 00:23:17,179
And we have a housing crisis in Medford.

305
00:23:17,539 --> 00:23:18,920
My generation is boxed out.

306
00:23:19,080 --> 00:23:19,700
We're boxed out.

307
00:23:20,100 --> 00:23:21,800
I graduated Medford High in 2015.

308
00:23:22,561 --> 00:23:32,423
Most of my friends have moved to a big city because they're like, well, I could stay here until I'm 40 and save up with my parents and then buy a house.

309
00:23:32,883 --> 00:23:35,284
Or I could go start my life in another city and start renting.

310
00:23:37,428 --> 00:23:43,214
The funny thing is, right, if you look at a lot of spaces to rent in Medford, it's outrageous.

311
00:23:43,734 --> 00:23:46,637
Locust Street apartments are about $3,000 for a studio.

312
00:23:47,278 --> 00:23:47,818
I looked there.

313
00:23:47,838 --> 00:23:50,161
I was like, OK, this is not realistic.

314
00:23:50,561 --> 00:23:51,622
I was renting in DC.

315
00:23:51,662 --> 00:23:53,284
My studio was $1,500 a month.

316
00:23:53,524 --> 00:23:56,387
That was already way too much money, $1,500 a month.

317
00:23:56,467 --> 00:24:00,270
We're talking studios and one bedrooms at $3,000 in Medford.

318
00:24:02,172 --> 00:24:04,354
And so how do we curb that issue, right?

319
00:24:04,374 --> 00:24:05,675
And this is all in line with equity.

320
00:24:05,855 --> 00:24:07,276
This all falls under the question.

321
00:24:09,317 --> 00:24:12,339
We don't have an Office of Affordable Housing in Medford.

322
00:24:12,379 --> 00:24:14,381
We don't have a land trust.

323
00:24:15,301 --> 00:24:19,464
There are a lot of actions we can take to really move forward in that space.

324
00:24:20,945 --> 00:24:29,713
And to me, Mystic Avenue is that golden opportunity of revising our zoning laws, looking at how do we make this space work for affordable housing.

325
00:24:29,773 --> 00:24:35,119
I mean, not to mention Medford is currently, I think it's either 7 or 8% out of affordable housing citywide right now.

326
00:24:35,479 --> 00:24:37,120
By state law, we're supposed to be at 10%.

327
00:24:38,101 --> 00:24:39,663
So once again, we're breaking state law.

328
00:24:41,625 --> 00:24:48,512
That's where you allow those 40 Bs, which are apartment buildings that are 20% affordable housing, to open up here in Medford.

329
00:24:48,532 --> 00:24:51,294
We've had multiple proposals and yet we pumped the brakes on them.

330
00:24:52,656 --> 00:24:56,380
I think Medford's at the point where we've been pumping the brakes for so long.

331
00:24:56,900 --> 00:25:03,607
Medford in so many ways, when you look at the physical elements, not the cultural, not the people, but the physical elements, it feels like we're in 1960.

332
00:25:05,148 --> 00:25:13,631
When you look at the layout of Medford Square, when you look at our housing stock, when you look at Mystic Ave, these are incredible opportunities.

333
00:25:13,912 --> 00:25:17,053
And you look at Malden downtown, they flipped in the past five years.

334
00:25:17,553 --> 00:25:21,194
They are accessible, they are walkable, they have public transportation.

335
00:25:21,495 --> 00:25:23,475
That's what we need to be fighting for in Medford.

336
00:25:23,936 --> 00:25:26,917
And we need champions at the local level that are advocating for this.

337
00:25:28,101 --> 00:25:30,503
Medford Square, I'm nearly 25, right?

338
00:25:31,364 --> 00:25:33,086
Medford Square has been a conversation my whole life.

339
00:25:33,707 --> 00:25:35,829
We're gonna get to work on Medford Square.

340
00:25:35,849 --> 00:25:43,956
And I had, I won't lie, I had points of sincere hope when there were, there's been three different redraws of Medford Square.

341
00:25:44,477 --> 00:25:45,718
We don't need another study.

342
00:25:45,978 --> 00:25:48,040
We don't need another redraw of Medford Square.

343
00:25:48,080 --> 00:25:49,221
Nothing's changed since then.

344
00:25:49,982 --> 00:25:50,302
We need a

345
00:25:50,943 --> 00:25:53,885
put that plan in action and put the shovel in the ground and get to work.

346
00:25:54,385 --> 00:26:00,009
I think the reason we kick that can down the road is because construction is going to be uncomfortable and people are going to be upset.

347
00:26:00,650 --> 00:26:04,532
The construction is worth it on the flip side, but I think that's why we continue to push it because

348
00:26:05,813 --> 00:26:10,435
truly redrawing Medford Square is going to be uncomfortable for residents, for small businesses.

349
00:26:10,455 --> 00:26:12,436
There's going to have to be temporary solutions.

350
00:26:13,136 --> 00:26:15,958
But now it's been 25 years of avoiding the conversation.

351
00:26:16,718 --> 00:26:18,919
You're letting me talk for too long.

352
00:26:18,999 --> 00:26:20,420
I got a question about the charter.

353
00:26:20,440 --> 00:26:27,483
So if that were to happen, would it, it would be an option to go to at-large representation where you'd have to vote on that?

354
00:26:27,603 --> 00:26:38,329
I'm so glad you asked about this because I made a mental note that this process, there's a lot of misinformation about this process on the public front.

355
00:26:38,389 --> 00:26:39,830
I think that's no one's fault.

356
00:26:39,890 --> 00:26:41,170
No one really explains it to us.

357
00:26:41,711 --> 00:26:44,932
But the way it works is the council votes for the review.

358
00:26:45,953 --> 00:26:49,017
That then goes to the statehouse and is voted on at the statehouse.

359
00:26:49,858 --> 00:26:55,084
What the statehouse is voting on is just to start a commission to evaluate our charter.

360
00:26:55,845 --> 00:27:01,972
The commission then comes up with a proposed charter, which is then voted on by the community.

361
00:27:02,713 --> 00:27:09,117
It's a long process to even get to that point, which is why so many candidates are talking about this with urgency.

362
00:27:09,437 --> 00:27:15,642
We understand if we even get to work immediately, we have a two-year road ahead of us before we even have something tangible in front of us.

363
00:27:17,323 --> 00:27:21,345
But that commission will make a recommendation about the charter.

364
00:27:21,385 --> 00:27:24,928
So it can include things like ward representation and at large.

365
00:27:25,588 --> 00:27:31,352
It can include, you know, term limits, which I'm very incredibly in favor of.

366
00:27:32,192 --> 00:27:36,214
But of course, you know, just because I'm in favor of it doesn't mean it needs to happen.

367
00:27:36,254 --> 00:27:49,499
Like I understand that if I'm fortunate enough to be elected that I'd be representing 58,000 people and always want to listen to folks from all walks of life and every opinion and then evaluate from there what makes the most sense for a city like Medford.

368
00:27:50,859 --> 00:27:54,321
You know, it reviews the power balance between the mayor and the council.

369
00:27:55,221 --> 00:27:57,422
We have a really, really strong mayor in Medford.

370
00:27:58,742 --> 00:28:05,308
Like, you know, Malden also has a strong mayor, but they don't yield as much power as the mayor does in Medford.

371
00:28:05,368 --> 00:28:06,729
And it's a lot on the mayor.

372
00:28:06,869 --> 00:28:09,511
It's a lot, because they basically, every decision falls under them.

373
00:28:09,851 --> 00:28:10,812
That's a large decision.

374
00:28:10,832 --> 00:28:14,094
You know, our council passes the budget, and they can do a lot of resolutions.

375
00:28:15,235 --> 00:28:19,619
But a lot of big initiatives, it's on the shoulders of the mayor to do that in two years.

376
00:28:19,639 --> 00:28:20,620
You have two years.

377
00:28:21,260 --> 00:28:26,222
to prove yourself, and really you have 12 months to prove yourself before you're in re-election again.

378
00:28:26,622 --> 00:28:27,562
That's a lot to ask.

379
00:28:27,622 --> 00:28:29,283
Working for Stephanie, I saw that.

380
00:28:30,203 --> 00:28:41,307
I was blown away by what Stephanie could do in four years between, you know, funding the incredible project that was the police station, that was a lot of money, getting a brand new library, Riverside Park.

381
00:28:41,327 --> 00:28:46,009
Those are just a few things that I was like, wow, that's what a really strong administrator can do in a few years.

382
00:28:47,369 --> 00:28:49,951
But she was always fighting off her real act, you know, and that's tough.

383
00:28:49,971 --> 00:28:54,873
So I think charter review just to get to a healthier place would be a four-year mayor.

384
00:28:54,974 --> 00:28:59,256
To have anyone who's mayor just be more productive in that office, you know.

385
00:28:59,756 --> 00:29:04,759
Yeah, and you've shared a lot about the community of Medford, and it's clear that you have a lot that you appreciate about it.

386
00:29:05,819 --> 00:29:07,120
Sorry if I'm going on.

387
00:29:07,740 --> 00:29:08,361
No, you're good.

388
00:29:09,441 --> 00:29:10,361
It's very informative.

389
00:29:10,421 --> 00:29:15,883
I think that's part of what I'm enjoying about this process is getting a deeper understanding of some of these issues.

390
00:29:15,963 --> 00:29:18,283
We just hear the terms, and they're not clear what they mean.

391
00:29:18,303 --> 00:29:21,544
TODD KERPELMAN So many people have explained charter review to you at this point.

392
00:29:21,584 --> 00:29:22,304
I feel bad.

393
00:29:22,884 --> 00:29:25,005
And I know it's more to get the word out there.

394
00:29:25,025 --> 00:29:28,206
But thanks for bearing with all the candidates while we explain this.

395
00:29:29,226 --> 00:29:33,047
It took me months as a candidate to understand this process.

396
00:29:34,627 --> 00:29:37,448
Being a candidate has been so informative.

397
00:29:37,528 --> 00:29:41,470
I mean, I can't tell you how much I know about trees now.

398
00:29:41,490 --> 00:29:45,672
I knew the importance of trees, but I don't think I understood in depth.

399
00:29:46,152 --> 00:29:50,314
Like, some trees have a life of 90 years, you know, the same as a human.

400
00:29:51,615 --> 00:29:53,155
I just, I never thought of it that way.

401
00:29:53,175 --> 00:29:55,577
Growing up, I was like, trees live for hundreds of years.

402
00:29:55,897 --> 00:29:58,338
And that is true about some trees, but not all species.

403
00:29:59,858 --> 00:30:03,320
In trees, right, talking about equity, trees are an issue of equity.

404
00:30:03,800 --> 00:30:09,423
South Medford, South Medford, some streets have one tree on the entire street.

405
00:30:10,143 --> 00:30:12,004
That is not true in Western North Medford.

