421
00:31:18,676 --> 00:31:27,240
That shouldn't be decided by any elected official because, you know, I am one person and I have my life, my income, my scenario, my housing.

422
00:31:27,680 --> 00:31:30,821
I don't have the same scenario as 58,000 other people.

423
00:31:30,861 --> 00:31:33,082
We have to be mindful of everyone's situation.

424
00:31:34,022 --> 00:31:41,407
For example, as I was door-knocking North Medford, I talked to a lot of seniors that said, David, I'm excited.

425
00:31:41,427 --> 00:31:46,610
I just want you to know if you increase taxes, I'll probably lose my home.

426
00:31:47,050 --> 00:31:47,711
I'm widowed.

427
00:31:47,731 --> 00:31:49,111
I live on Social Security.

428
00:31:50,012 --> 00:31:50,952
I'll lose this house.

429
00:31:51,973 --> 00:31:58,420
So I think that there's a world that can work for both, where if we do have to increase taxes, there can be a senior exemption.

430
00:31:58,701 --> 00:32:02,785
Just because we need to increase revenue in this city doesn't mean we need to box out a whole generation.

431
00:32:03,106 --> 00:32:07,811
But again, I think the best space for that is a ballot question, because something like that should go to the people.

432
00:32:08,111 --> 00:32:09,933
That should be weighted on by every individual.

433
00:32:11,515 --> 00:32:12,516
That'll be interesting.

434
00:32:12,556 --> 00:32:14,278
And that could be up next election.

435
00:32:14,358 --> 00:32:19,503
I mean, depending on how this election goes, it'll be really interesting to see what the next few years look like.

436
00:32:19,563 --> 00:32:19,944
Yeah.

437
00:32:20,464 --> 00:32:20,704
Great.

438
00:32:20,764 --> 00:32:21,545
Well, thank you so much.

439
00:32:21,605 --> 00:32:23,868
I'm going to switch to a little bit of a personal question.

440
00:32:23,888 --> 00:32:23,968
Sure.

441
00:32:24,008 --> 00:32:24,268
Yes.

442
00:32:24,408 --> 00:32:24,508
OK.

443
00:32:24,528 --> 00:32:25,970
These are meant to be fun.

444
00:32:26,130 --> 00:32:26,270
OK.

445
00:32:26,410 --> 00:32:30,614
So if you could share something about yourself that you think might surprise us.

446
00:32:31,355 --> 00:32:32,737
Oh, that's a great question.

447
00:32:33,577 --> 00:32:34,398
Something fun.

448
00:32:35,660 --> 00:32:37,160
I did a lot of theater in high school.

449
00:32:37,561 --> 00:32:39,421
Really loved, loved, loved it.

450
00:32:40,121 --> 00:32:48,204
Miss Grant and Erin Keith are two incredible individuals who I believe still do all the shows at the middle school and the high school.

451
00:32:48,224 --> 00:32:52,645
And those days just are so impactful on you.

452
00:32:52,665 --> 00:32:55,126
You know, also, like, I was a bit of a different kid, right?

453
00:32:55,166 --> 00:33:01,548
Like, I didn't, I was, I mean, I was class president, but I didn't also fit in really anywhere at the same time.

454
00:33:03,919 --> 00:33:04,700
I was just different.

455
00:33:04,760 --> 00:33:07,182
I didn't know how to explain it.

456
00:33:07,202 --> 00:33:12,687
You know, sometimes you just feel different, like you don't really fit in in a certain pocket, and I always kind of felt that way.

457
00:33:12,727 --> 00:33:18,453
But theater, I had that space where you could just be so weird and there was no judgment.

458
00:33:18,893 --> 00:33:22,076
I think when you find that place at a young age, it builds confidence.

459
00:33:22,857 --> 00:33:26,838
that you like feel hopefully like securing yourself to do the stuff that you're doing now.

460
00:33:26,898 --> 00:33:27,118
Right.

461
00:33:27,458 --> 00:33:27,918
Exactly.

462
00:33:27,978 --> 00:33:28,158
Right.

463
00:33:28,518 --> 00:33:31,019
The confidence you you're getting at such a big thing.

464
00:33:31,039 --> 00:33:33,439
It is that it is that confidence.

465
00:33:33,479 --> 00:33:34,800
Everyone's cool in their own way.

466
00:33:34,820 --> 00:33:39,041
It's just finding your own niche or the space that expands upon your best self.

467
00:33:39,221 --> 00:33:39,541
Right.

468
00:33:39,921 --> 00:33:43,802
I think we're all still always experiencing that, especially after a pandemic.

469
00:33:45,560 --> 00:33:47,840
I think we all had a reevaluation of like, who am I?

470
00:33:47,920 --> 00:33:48,681
What do I care about?

471
00:33:48,701 --> 00:33:49,841
What am I passionate about?

472
00:33:51,421 --> 00:33:53,321
And what do I prioritize in life?

473
00:33:53,541 --> 00:33:54,061
Oh, for sure.

474
00:33:54,402 --> 00:33:54,622
Yeah.

475
00:33:54,722 --> 00:33:58,302
I talk a lot about how the pandemic kind of shrunk things for us.

476
00:33:58,702 --> 00:33:58,982
Yes.

477
00:33:59,342 --> 00:34:00,663
Like everything became small.

478
00:34:00,703 --> 00:34:02,803
And I think in a lot of ways that was good.

479
00:34:02,843 --> 00:34:04,523
I think especially for connection, right?

480
00:34:04,563 --> 00:34:06,024
Connecting to our smaller communities.

481
00:34:06,544 --> 00:34:09,264
I got the opportunity to meet a lot more people in my neighborhood, right?

482
00:34:09,284 --> 00:34:09,824
Yeah.

483
00:34:09,964 --> 00:34:13,845
I don't know that I would have had otherwise had I been not forced to stay home all the time.

484
00:34:14,105 --> 00:34:16,107
I know, but you're a great example, right?

485
00:34:16,147 --> 00:34:21,091
Like, you know your neighbors better and you're more involved in local government, right?

486
00:34:21,131 --> 00:34:22,672
Would you say that after the past few years?

487
00:34:22,712 --> 00:34:32,080
And I think again, some super small silver linings to the pandemic, but that was one of them is our community is really paying attention now in a wonderful way.

488
00:34:32,640 --> 00:34:35,522
We should hold our local officials to the same standard.

489
00:34:35,883 --> 00:34:38,385
We hold a member of Congress or president of the United States.

490
00:34:39,825 --> 00:34:50,708
Because you should always be a good person, you should always respect others, and you should put the best interest forward for a healthy planet, a healthy community, accessibility and equity.

491
00:34:51,288 --> 00:34:58,390
And so I'm hoping those are all results of really the past few years of people getting tuned back into their neighborhood, their community.

492
00:34:59,419 --> 00:35:03,641
you know, really having like a mindset that how am I affecting my block?

493
00:35:03,861 --> 00:35:06,443
How am I shaping my neighborhood, my community?

494
00:35:06,463 --> 00:35:09,524
Because it really is, it's on all of us, right?

495
00:35:09,564 --> 00:35:12,286
It's not on like our seven counselors alone.

496
00:35:12,746 --> 00:35:16,788
It's on all of us as activists and community members to take that initiative up.

497
00:35:17,849 --> 00:35:18,109
Yeah.

498
00:35:18,649 --> 00:35:22,891
Have you ever gotten any advice that, you know, really stuck with you that you'd want to pass on to other people?

499
00:35:23,372 --> 00:35:23,712
Yes.

500
00:35:24,572 --> 00:35:25,473
This is a good question.

501
00:35:26,678 --> 00:35:28,719
I have a few quotes in mind.

502
00:35:28,739 --> 00:35:38,442
I don't know that this is so much advice as a nugget of my father's life he shared with me that I just always carry with me.

503
00:35:38,522 --> 00:35:44,783
But my dad met my mom at a church in South Medford on a Wednesday.

504
00:35:44,983 --> 00:35:45,724
They were at mass.

505
00:35:46,404 --> 00:35:49,185
And the priest introduced my dad to my mom.

506
00:35:50,578 --> 00:35:55,080
and literally my dad proposed seven days later in that exact spot.

507
00:35:55,721 --> 00:35:58,682
He knew her for a week before he proposed and they're still married today.

508
00:35:59,943 --> 00:36:07,447
It's kind of unreal and they have four great children and some grandchildren as well and my parents are just

509
00:36:08,957 --> 00:36:11,420
do we bicker, of course, but they're everything to me.

510
00:36:11,640 --> 00:36:19,087
And my dad said, he said this at the time when, you know, my grandparents, my dad came home and he said, I'm engaged.

511
00:36:19,127 --> 00:36:20,668
My grandparents were like, oh, yeah, sure.

512
00:36:20,969 --> 00:36:21,950
Like, they had never met my mom.

513
00:36:21,970 --> 00:36:22,590
They're like, to who?

514
00:36:22,690 --> 00:36:23,611
Who are you engaged to?

515
00:36:23,791 --> 00:36:24,952
He said, Nancy Cicchini.

516
00:36:24,992 --> 00:36:26,934
She lives, you know, she lives on the hillside.

517
00:36:26,954 --> 00:36:27,335
And they were like.

518
00:36:27,775 --> 00:36:28,615
You're making this up.

519
00:36:28,655 --> 00:36:34,497
My dad had to bring my mom over to be like, this is the woman I'm marrying, which I don't blame my grandparents.

520
00:36:34,537 --> 00:36:40,559
But my dad said to my grandparents, when you know and you know you know, confidence replaces fear.

521
00:36:42,039 --> 00:36:44,480
And that's always just been a powerful thing.

522
00:36:44,520 --> 00:36:47,521
I've had moments in my life of so much self-doubt.

523
00:36:48,721 --> 00:36:52,082
I went to University of New Hampshire my first semester of undergrad.

524
00:36:53,025 --> 00:36:54,086
And I was so unhappy.

525
00:36:54,887 --> 00:36:57,810
And I actually transferred in the middle of the year to UMass Lowell.

526
00:36:58,451 --> 00:37:04,798
And I remember I was so scared, but simultaneously it was this pure feeling of confidence.

527
00:37:07,401 --> 00:37:09,744
And I carry that with me now.

528
00:37:10,104 --> 00:37:11,285
I was scared to do this.

529
00:37:11,365 --> 00:37:13,648
I was running for city council as a,

530
00:37:15,163 --> 00:37:16,464
It's an intimidating thing.

531
00:37:16,484 --> 00:37:31,077
You're running to represent 58,000 lives and understand their concerns, hear their concerns, and balance their concerns so that you're trying to give everyone what they envision is what their happy life is.

532
00:37:31,198 --> 00:37:32,779
And that's no easy feat.

533
00:37:34,240 --> 00:37:41,206
But I try to let, for me, the confidence overwhelm the fear of, I'm scared, but it feels like

534
00:37:41,867 --> 00:37:45,208
you're being called to this moment to take action in your community.

535
00:37:45,228 --> 00:37:47,388
And I hope everyone feels that way.

536
00:37:47,428 --> 00:37:49,149
Like running for office is scared.

537
00:37:49,169 --> 00:37:54,350
Whether you're listening to this in Medford or some other community, I hope you consider too.

538
00:37:54,410 --> 00:37:57,451
I mean, Lori Trahan always said this to me, who is my former boss.

539
00:37:57,911 --> 00:38:00,071
She always said, lean in, lean in.

540
00:38:00,271 --> 00:38:02,992
It's scary, but lean into the fights, the hard fights.

541
00:38:03,852 --> 00:38:07,733
And I hope everyone in the city does that over the next two years.

542
00:38:07,773 --> 00:38:11,154
And I hope if I'm fortunate enough to be elected, people hold my feet to the fire.

543
00:38:12,094 --> 00:38:13,975
as we're sitting next to a fire.

544
00:38:14,736 --> 00:38:25,201
I hope that the people hold me and the other, if fortunate enough, other six counselors accountable, hold the mayor accountable, hold your state reps accountable, your state senators.

545
00:38:25,542 --> 00:38:27,763
You know, these people, they made promises to you.

546
00:38:28,143 --> 00:38:30,184
And they, you know, Rome wasn't built in a day.

547
00:38:30,204 --> 00:38:34,186
It's not going to happen overnight, but you should really see some,

548
00:38:35,687 --> 00:38:38,748
good transformation in Medford in the next few years.

549
00:38:39,588 --> 00:38:56,611
And hopefully that's transformation we all benefit from, whether it's a revitalized Medford Square, an infrastructure plan for our streets, dramatically better Medford High School, continuing, like look at our recreation program as a young department, what they've been able to do since 2015.

550
00:38:56,711 --> 00:39:05,013
We have to continue to provide resources to build out Medford Rec and get trees, trees on every street.

551
00:39:06,573 --> 00:39:15,736
And so I hope that that's the transformation we see in the next few years, that people start to really, you know, this community has so much pride.

552
00:39:16,656 --> 00:39:17,616
So much pride.

553
00:39:17,776 --> 00:39:18,756
It's blown me away.

554
00:39:18,796 --> 00:39:23,497
That's really like, we've knocked about 9,000 doors the past six months.

555
00:39:24,118 --> 00:39:25,218
Our team's definitely tired.

556
00:39:25,918 --> 00:39:29,981
But everyone's shared so many stories with us along the way, and we carry those stories.

557
00:39:30,061 --> 00:39:33,503
And a lot of them are what people love about Medford, what they see in Medford.

558
00:39:34,143 --> 00:39:38,826
And so we just need a city that really reflects what people already see in the city, you know?

559
00:39:40,548 --> 00:39:43,029
I'm so hopeful and confident we can do that.

560
00:39:44,070 --> 00:39:45,471
And I just, I always say, you know,

561
00:39:47,241 --> 00:39:53,789
It matters so much what happens at City Hall, even though people don't watch it like they watch CNN or Fox News.

562
00:39:54,730 --> 00:39:58,094
Your access to the ballot box is decided at City Hall, not the U.S.

563
00:39:58,154 --> 00:39:58,615
Capitol.

564
00:39:59,055 --> 00:40:01,839
The state of your street is decided at City Hall, not the U.S.

565
00:40:01,879 --> 00:40:02,279
Capitol.

566
00:40:03,941 --> 00:40:05,462
And so I hope people really feel that.

567
00:40:05,742 --> 00:40:06,483
I think they are.

568
00:40:07,444 --> 00:40:09,626
We keep saying we're cautiously optimistic.

569
00:40:11,247 --> 00:40:17,572
I can give my final ask to listeners, but I don't want to cut you off if it's not time.

570
00:40:17,592 --> 00:40:18,673
I think you're getting there.

571
00:40:18,793 --> 00:40:20,114
Awesome.

572
00:40:20,374 --> 00:40:24,177
My big ask is that people get out to vote.

573
00:40:24,437 --> 00:40:25,458
You get out to vote.

574
00:40:25,558 --> 00:40:27,640
I mean, I don't know when this will be posted right now.

575
00:40:28,100 --> 00:40:30,022
We're eight days out from an election.

576
00:40:32,303 --> 00:40:37,888
this election is pivotal between the federal funds coming and just speaking to who are we as a community?

577
00:40:38,188 --> 00:40:39,469
What do we believe in?

578
00:40:39,770 --> 00:40:48,357
Do we want people with energy, people that are really gonna do their personal best to take action and have Medford put our best foot forward these next two years?

579
00:40:49,638 --> 00:40:50,879
So I ask that you get out to vote.

580
00:40:51,259 --> 00:40:53,141
